ime-events.schema.json:1543:          \"$ref\": \"#/$defs/ErrorNotificationRealtimeEvent\"\ndocs/realtime-events.schema.json:1559:        \"RealtimeReplayStrategy\": {\ndocs/realtime-events.schema.json:1565:          \"title\": \"RealtimeReplayStrategy\",\ndocs/realtime-events.schema.json:1647:          \"$ref\": \"#/$defs/RealtimeReplayStrategy\",\ndocs/realtime-events.schema.json:1749:  \"title\": \"Storyteller Realtime Contracts\"\ndocs/frontend-design-foundation.md:15:- Depth: shared surface and button shadows support the soft, paper-like panel\ndocs/architecture-overview.md:11:Storyteller is a full-stack application with a browser client, a backend-owned workflow engine, durable relational state, durable object storage, and resumable background jobs.\ndocs/architecture-overview.md:35:1. Secrets control: provider credentials live in local `secrets.yaml` and must never enter the browser.\ndocs/architecture-overview.md:44:Composition and narration are long-running operations that cannot safely live inside request threads or browser memory. They need server-side jobs because:\ndocs/architecture-overview.md:57:- `api/`: HTTP routes and websocket endpoints\ndocs/architecture-overview.md:96:- `infra/compose/docker-compose.yml`: local frontend, backend, PostgreSQL, file-backed GCS emulator, and browser QA services\ndocs/architecture-overview.md:99:- `tools/webapp-qa/`: containerized browser automation support\ndocs/chat-to-ui-actions.md:36:| `pitches`     | `regenerate_pitches`, `refine_pitch`, `select_pitch`                              | Covers \u201cgive me more options,\u201d \u201crevise that pitch,\u201d and \u201cpick this pitch\u201d flows.                      |\ndocs/planning-funnel-e2e-test.md:33:- No browser automation is involved; this test covers the backend contract that the workspace UI consumes.\ndocs/secrets-and-local-config.md:47:That means a local developer can copy the example file, add a Gemini key, and start the full stack without exposing the key to the browser.\ndocs/secrets-and-local-config.md:153:The frontend never receives the Gemini API key. The browser only talks to the FastAPI backend, and all Gemini access stays in backend-owned services and adapters.\ndocs/README.md:15:- `realtime-events.md`: session-channel contract, live event families, replay rules, and local auth assumptions\ndocs/README.md:16:- `realtime-events.schema.json`: machine-readable schema bundle for subscription frames and session events\ndocs/README.md:19:- `system-diagram.md`: one-page runtime diagram for browser, API, worker, storage, and Gemini flows\ndocs/chat-to-ui-actions.schema.json:303:              \"$ref\": \"#/$defs/WorkflowStage\"\ndocs/chat-to-ui-actions.schema.json:2293:        \"WorkflowStage\": {\ndocs/chat-to-ui-actions.schema.json:2306:          \"title\": \"WorkflowStage\",\ndocs/chat-to-ui-actions.schema.json:2668:              \"$ref\": \"#/$defs/WorkflowStage\"\ndocs/chat-to-ui-actions.schema.json:4658:        \"WorkflowStage\": {\ndocs/chat-to-ui-actions.schema.json:4671:          \"title\": \"WorkflowStage\",\ndocs/frontend-state-architecture.md:25:- The local runtime store keeps websocket/event-stream concerns separate from\ndocs/frontend-state-architecture.md:53:Runtime-only updates for future realtime work:\ndocs/system-diagram.md:3:This diagram shows the intended runtime shape for Storyteller after the core session, worker, and realtime prompts are built. It documents where session resume, durable event history, realtime delivery, and long-running jobs belong.\ndocs/system-diagram.md:7:    Browser[\"Browser UI<br/>React + Vite<br/>sessions home, chat pane, workflow pane\"]\ndocs/system-diagram.md:9:    WS[\"WebSocket session stream<br/>replay recent events + deliver live progress\"]\ndocs/system-diagram.md:15:    Browser -->|\"HTTP actions and reads\"| API\ndocs/system-diagram.md:16:    API -->|\"resume session snapshot\"| Browser\ndocs/system-diagram.md:17:    Browser <-->|\"subscribe / receive live updates\"| WS\ndocs/system-diagram.md:20:    WS -->|\"replay recent events and current job state\"| Postgres\ndocs/system-diagram.md:34:- The browser never calls Gemini directly.\ndocs/system-diagram.md:36:- WebSockets deliver progress, but durable state still lives in PostgreSQL and object storage.\ndocs/event-taxonomy.md:5:UI-to-chat coherence, and later real-time fan-out without relying on browser-only state.\ndocs/event-taxonomy.md:111:from app.models import SelectionKind, WorkflowStage\ndocs/event-taxonomy.md:118:    stage=WorkflowStage.GENRE,\ndocs/domain-model.md:8:- Workflow truth lives on the backend, not in browser-only UI state.\ndocs/domain-model.md:11:- Composition and audio are long-running workflows backed by durable records, not one-shot request responses.\ndocs/domain-model.md:84:- `frontend/src/features/session/workflowStages.ts`\ndocs/domain-model.md:90:The same four-state lifecycle should be used for stage rows and for generated artifacts that can become stale.\ndocs/domain-model.md:160:The system should support these reopen flows without guessing from UI state:\ndocs/domain-model.md:177:- Frontend mirror for rendering and client-side navigation: `frontend/src/features/session/workflowStages.ts`\ndocs/domain-model.md:183:- Keep the literal stage-state values stable once they enter database rows or websocket payloads.\ndocs/contributing.md:31:- Treat the backend as the source of truth for workflow stage, job progress, and AI side effects. The browser reflects state; it does not own it.\ndocs/adr/README.md:9:- `0001-core-runtime-architecture.md`: backend-owned AI calls, durable Postgres session state, file-backed GCS assets, websocket live updates, separate workers for long-running jobs, and soft planning constraints\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:12:- the browser cannot hold Gemini credentials or call provider APIs directly\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:26:- The browser talks only to backend APIs and websocket streams.\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:49:Session resume should come from durable state, not browser cache. The event history is part of the product, not just an internal log, because it supports replay, auditability, and UI-to-chat echoes.\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:53:Large generated files should not live inside PostgreSQL rows.\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:61:### 4. Live progress uses websocket delivery\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:63:The browser needs live updates during composition and audio generation, and those updates need to remain tied to durable backend state.\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:66:- WebSockets handle session progress, job status, and incremental event delivery.\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:69:The websocket channel is a delivery mechanism, not the source of truth. If a socket drops, the session must still be recoverable from PostgreSQL and storage.\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:77:- The API remains responsible for request handling, policy checks, and websocket fan-out.\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:95:- Secrets stay out of the browser.\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:104:- Websocket delivery and worker orchestration add coordination work that later prompts must implement carefully.\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:109:- Put websocket endpoints under backend API ownership, not in the frontend dev server.\ndocs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:112:- Resist pushing model calls into route handlers or browser-side helpers.\n", "command": "/bin/zsh -lc 'rg -n \"session events|realtime|websocket|ws\" infra backend/README.md docs -S'", "exit_code": 0, "id": "item_23", "status": "completed", "type": "command_execution"}, "type": "item.completed"}, "task_display_context": {"event_number": 48, "prompt_index": 63, "prompt_name": "62 \u2014 Composition Streaming Events", "prompt_total": 100}, "timestap": "2026-04-02T07:21:34-07:00"}
